d at worst degraded and exploited. In Passionate Enlightenment, Miranda Shaw argues to the contrary and presents extensive evidence of the outspoken and independent female founders of the Tantric movement and their creative role in shaping its distinctive vision of gender relations and sacred sexuality. Including a new preface by the author, this Princeton Classics edition makes an essential work available for new audiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aTantric Buddhism. 0aWomen in Tantric BuddhismzIndia. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / General (see also PHILOSOPHY / Buddhist).2bisacsh  aAbhidharma.  aAndrocentrism.  aAnother Woman.  aAsceticism.  aAttunement.  aAvalokitesvara.  aAwareness.  aBhairava.  aBodhicitta.  aBodhisattva.  aBuddhahood.  aBuddhism.  aBuddhist ethics.  aBuddhist pilgrimage.  aBuddhist texts.  aCelibacy.  aChakra.  aCircumambulation.  aCourtesan.  aDeference.  aDeity.  aDoctrine.  aDominatrix.  aDukkha.  aEnlightenment (spiritual).  aEquanimity.  aFaith healing.  aFasting.  aFemale promiscuity.  aFeminist theology.  aFive Dhyani Buddhas.  aGender role.  aGreat Goddess.  aHeruka.  aHevajra.  aHindu priest.  aIconography.  aInclusivism.  aIndependent woman.  aIndication (medicine).  aKelsang Gyatso.  aLibido.  aLiterature.  aLuipa.  aMaithuna.  aMale gaze.  aMandala.  aMantra.  aMeditation.  aMetaphysics.  aMilarepa.  aMircea Eliade.  aMonasticism.  aNiguma.  aPerfection of Wisdom.  aPhilosophy.  aPratityasamutpada.  aPuranas.  aReligion.  aReligious ecstasy.  aReligious experience.  aReligious text.  aRenunciation.  aRita Gross.  aRite.  aRitual purification.  aSacred prostitution.  aSahaja.  aSamadhi.  aSanskrit.  aSaraha.  aScholasticism.  aSelf-denial